ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Brunei has experienced the first death out of a total of 17 cases of
HFMD -- a rough case fatality rate of 5.9 percent. HFMD is caused by
enteroviruses, among which coxsackievirus A16 (CA16) is the most
common etiologic agent. Usually no complications of HFMD are caused
by CA16 infection, although aseptic or viral meningitis may occur
occasionally. A second common cause of HFMD is enterovirus 71(EV71).
In addition to HFMD, EV71 may also cause aseptic or viral meningitis,
encephalitis, or a polio-like paralysis. EV71 meningitis or
encephalitis may on rare occasions be fatal.
Cases of fatal encephalitis occurred during widespread outbreaks of
HFMD in Bulgaria in 1975 (29 deaths), Malaysia in 1997 (29 deaths)
and Taiwan in 1998 (78 deaths). In the 1998 epidemic several
enteroviruses were involved. However, enterovirus 71 infection was
associated with most, if not all, of the serious clinical
manifestations and with nearly all deaths. Most of those who died
were younger than 5 years, and the majority died of pulmonary edema
and pulmonary hemorrhage.
No effective treatments are available. General treatment is
palliative. Preventive measures are focused on enforcement of
personal hygiene and public awareness campaigns.
Since the advent of the 1998 outbreak, Department of Health (DOH) of
Taiwan has determined the pattern of the annual seasonal HFMD
epidemic, the peak of which tends to fall in the beginning of July.
The DOH schedules the reminder campaign according to this pattern.
The disease has been brought under control. The Taiwan example can be
used as a role model for any countries which may encounter the same
problem.
Situated in Southeastern Asia, bordering the South China Sea and
Malaysia, Brunei is a tiny independent country with an area of 5770
sq km. Brunei is known chiefly for the astounding wealth of its
Sultan, its tax-free, subsidised society, and the fact that
(statistically at least) its population enjoys one of the highest per
capita incomes on earth. Map of Brunei can be accessed at:
<http://www.cia.gov/cia/publications/factbook/geos/bx.html>.
Picture of HFMD hand lesions:
<http://dermnet.com/image.cfm?passedArrayIndex=6&moduleID=24&moduleGroupID=327>
- Mod.RY]
